  <section>
    <title>Research</title>

    <project>
      <name>Type Theory for Higher-Order Stateful Concurrency</name>
      <description>Project aims to develop dependent type theory for verifying programs with realistic concurrency</description>
      <comment>Part of dissertation research</comment>
      <comment>Derives heavily from Hoare Type Theory (Morrisett et al.)</comment>
      <comment>Initial effort was successful, focus is now on refining the theory</comment>
    </project>

    <project>
      <name>Complexity Bounds for Lock-Free Concurrency</name>
      <description>Proved several lower-bound results for lock-free linearizable algorithms</description>
      <comment>Developed equivalent notion of lock-freedom for implementations of blocking synchronization constructs</comment>
      <comment>Showed time and space lower-bound for implementing n+1-CAS using n-CAS</comment>
      <comment>Showed combination of synchronous channels, choice, and transactions to be SAT-equivalent</comment>
      <comment>Currently working to publish results</comment>
    </project>

    <project>
      <name>Realizing Concurrent Functional Languages</name>
      <description>Investigated issues surrounding the practical realization of highly-concurrent functional languages</description>
      <comment>Master's thesis work</comment>
      <comment>Designed runtime architecture for supporting microthreading</comment>
      <comment>Designed lock-free thread scheduler and garbage collector</comment>
      <comment>Working to produce implementation of designs that can be integrated with a functional language frontend</comment>
    </project>

    <project>
      <name>Optimal Register Allocation for SSA Programs</name>
      <description>Independently reproduced results of Sebastian Hack (interference graphs for SSA programs are linear-time colorable)</description>
      <comment>Extended algorithm to apply to real architectures</comment>
      <comment>Possible future plans to implement for LLVM</comment>
    </project>

    <project>
      <name>Modern Features for Systems Programming Languages</name>
      <description>Focused on designing a language suitable for systems programming that incorporated features from ML and Haskell</description>
      <comment>Undergraduate work</comment>
      <comment>Published at regional conference level</comment>
    </project>

